# arvo-hash — backlog

## Concrete algorithms

Shipping order as consumers surface need:

- Fnv1a28: 28-bit FNV-1a. First migration target; matches
  hilavitkutin-str's existing const_fnv1a plus the 28-bit mask.
- Fnv1a32, Fnv1a64: wider FNV variants.
- XxHash64: when a faster non-cryptographic hash is wanted.
- Crc32: when checksum use cases surface (clause bytecode
  integrity, persistence file checksumming).

Each concrete algorithm lands as a unit struct implementing
Hasher<N>. HasherExt<N>::hash falls out via the blanket impl.

## Hilavitkutin-str migration

hilavitkutin-str const_fnv1a is the existing FNV implementation.
Once Fnv1a28 lands in arvo-hash, migrate hilavitkutin-str to
import or re-export that algo and adjust downstream use sites.

## Wider bit widths

If arvo-bits grows u128 backing for Bits (its own BACKLOG item),
arvo-hash gains Hash128-domain semantic aliases.

## Cryptographic hashes

Out of scope. arvo-hash targets non-cryptographic identity hashes.
A sibling arvo-crypto crate may appear if cryptographic hash
needs surface.

## Semantic aliases

NameHash, KeyHash, or similar named aliases beyond ContentHash
land once consumer patterns stabilise. The starting form is a
local alias in the consuming crate over ContentHash or Bits<N>;
promotion happens when a second consumer shares the alias.
